  "prompt": "What function do sclerenchyma cells serve?",
  "response": "Sclerenchyma cells primarily serve the function of **providing support and strengthening to plant structures.** They do this through their thick, rigid cell walls, which are heavily impregnated with lignin.\n\nHere's a more detailed breakdown:\n\n*   **Structural Support:** They provide rigidity and strength to stems, roots, leaves, and other plant parts, allowing plants to stand upright and resist bending or collapsing under their own weight or external forces.\n*   **Protection:** Their tough cell walls can protect delicate inner tissues from damage, such as from physical injury or herbivore attacks.\n*   **Support of Vascular Tissues:** They often support and reinforce the vascular bundles (xylem and phloem) which transport water and nutrients throughout the plant.\n*   **Specialized Functions:** In some cases, sclerenchyma cells also have specialized functions related to seed dispersal or other specific adaptations.\n\nIn essence, think of sclerenchyma as the \"skeleton\" or \"reinforcement bars\" of a plant, providing the necessary strength and support for its overall structure and survival.\n",
